{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17594465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17594465"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T10:48:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T10:48:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15316"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15316","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15316"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.23,0.06,0.71,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8007"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65909"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8007","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8007"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15316"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51355"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8133"},{"type":"tags","id":"8755"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19464"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22012"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65909"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA patient presents with jaundice. Imaging suggests an obstruction somewhere between the biliary canaliculi and the ampulla of Vater. Blood samples are sent for measurement of liver function, looking particularly at alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following patterns is most likely?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Elevated ALP and lower GGT","Elevated ALP and normal GGT","Normal ALP and elevated GGT","Elevated ALP and GGT","Lower ALP and GGT"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn biliary obstruction, there would be elevation of the alkaline phosphatase (ALP), gamma-glutamyltransferase (GGT), lactate dehydrogenase (LD) and to a lesser extent, the transaminases.  Thus both \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated ALP and GGT\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic findings. These enzymes are induced by cholestasis and their concurrent elevation is highly specific for biliary pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other patterns are less likely: \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated ALP and lower GGT\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevated ALP and normal GGT\u003C/strong\u003E are not typical patterns in biliary disease. Having \u003Cstrong\u003Enormal ALP and elevated GGT\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in other conditions but not typically in biliary obstruction. \u003Cstrong\u003ELower ALP and GGT\u003C/strong\u003E would not be expected in any form of biliary pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGGT elevation is more specific for biliary disease than ALP alone, as ALP can also be elevated in bone disease. When both are elevated, this strongly suggests a cholestatic picture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In obstructive biliary pathology, both alkaline phosphatase (ALP) and gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) are typically elevated","Concurrent elevation of ALP and GGT is more specific for biliary/cholestatic disease than elevation of either enzyme alone"],"references":["Joseph A, Samant H. Jaundice. 2023 Aug 8. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 31334972","amada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Gasmi B, Kleiner DE. Liver Histology: Diagnostic and Prognostic Features. Clin Liver Dis. 2020 Feb;24(1):61-74. doi: 10.1016/j.cld.2019.09.004. Epub 2019 Oct 31. PMID: 31753251; PMCID: PMC6986808"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51355"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15316"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51355","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51355"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-27T13:34:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T13:34:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8007"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65909"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attr